/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/onyxprotocol_p5_25_124/foundry_validation/F-001_Direct_underlying_donations_can_inflate/codex_stderr_attempt4.log:8076:/Users/zhanglongqin/.codex/sessions/2026/03/18/rollout-2026-03-18T20-30-22-019d00ec-f5f2-79e3-8217-d74bacf75f46.jsonl:146:{"timestamp":"2026-03-18T12:34:19.380Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"call_wo0fgIuR0Cd90seywHD7j79c","output":"Chunk ID: 4d0c39\nWall time: 0.0513 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1432\nOutput:\n# NFTLiquidation Vulnerability Report\n\n## Case summary\n- Target: `0xf10Bc5bE84640236C71173D1809038af4eE19002`\n- Source reviewed: `etherscan-contracts/0xf10Bc5bE84640236C71173D1809038af4eE19002/Contract.sol`\n- Architecture: proxy + implementation pattern is present in source (`NFTLiquidationProxy` + `NFTLiquidation`).\n- Constraint in this environment: runtime RPC checks to `127.0.0.1:8545` are blocked and `cast call`/`forge` network calls panic, so exploitability checks below are based on full source analysis and callable-path reasoning.\n\n## Confirmed vulnerability candidates (ranked)\n\n### 1. Critical: Untrusted market addresses + full-balance sweep in seize transfer flow\n- Location:\n  - `liquidateWithSingleRepay` / `liquidateWithSingleRepayV2`: lines 667-690\n  - `liquidateWithSingleRepayFresh`: lines 696-738\n  - `transferSeizedTokenFresh`: lines 740-764\n- Why vulnerable:\n  - `oTokenRepay` and `oTokenCollateral` are attacker-controlled and not validated as trusted Onyx markets.\n  - `transferSeizedTokenFresh` uses `seizedTokenAmount = balanceOf(address(this))` and transfers/redeems **all current balance**, not delta seized by this liquidation.\n  - The flow trusts external contracts for:\n    - debt (`borrowBalanceCurrent`)\n    - liquidation success (`liquidateBorrow == 0`)\n    - token movement APIs (`transfer`, `redeem`, `userTokens`, `underlying`)\n  - This enables a fake liquidation path that can execute seize-transfer logic without real repayment.\n- Impact:\n  - Any NFTs currently held by the liquidation contract can be swept to attacker through crafted calls.\n  - With malicious collateral wrappers, attacker can steer redemption/transfer behavior to arbitrary transferable NFT holdings of the contract.\n\n### 2. High: Missing “newly seized” accounting check\n- Location: `transferSeizedTokenFresh` lines 740-764.\n- Why vulnerable:\n  - There is no `beforeBalance` snapshot and no assertion tying transferred amount to liquidation result.\n  - Function empties existing inventory each call.\n- Impact:\n  - Public caller can drain previously accumulated seized collateral, including from prior liquidations.\n\n### 3. Medium (admin-scoped): fee setter validates wrong variable\n- Location: `setProtocolFeeMantissa` lines 941-946.\n- Why vulnerable:\n  - `require(protocolFeeMantissa <= 1e18, \"invalid fee\");` checks old state, not `_protocolFeeMantissa`.\n- Impact:\n  - Admin can set >100% fee accidentally/maliciously. Not directly public-exploitable, but severe governance/ops risk.\n\n## Exploitability checks (access control / liquidity / callable paths)\n\n### Access control\n- `liquidateWithSingleRepay` and `liquidateWithSingleRepayV2` are `external payable nonReentrant` with no role restriction.\n- Gating checks:\n  - `borrower != address(0)`\n  - `IComptroller(comptroller).getAccountLiquidity(borrower).shortfall > 0`\n  - `extraRepayAmount == 0` (internal transient guard)\n- No checks that `oTokenRepay`/`oTokenCollateral` are valid listed markets.\n\n### Callable-path viability\n- Attack path is viable if attacker can provide:\n  - A borrower currently in shortfall (`shortfall > 0`).\n  - A malicious `oTokenRepay` contract returning:\n    - `borrowBalanceCurrent(...) = 0`\n    - `liquidateBorrow(...) = 0`\n    - `mint(...) = 0`\n    - compatible `underlying()` behavior for zero-amount transfer path.\n  - A collateral path (`oTokenCollateral`) that causes `transferSeizedTokenFresh` to transfer valuable assets out.\n- With `repayAmount = 0`, token-transfer cost can be zero if call path accepts zero value operations.\n\n### Liquidity / profit realization\n- Primary extraction is NFTs from liquidation contract inventory.\n- Monetization requires selling NFTs (direct marketplace or NFT AMM / OTC route) into ETH.\n- If even one transferable NFT worth >0.1 ETH exists, threshold is satisfied.\n- Runtime pool checks could not be executed in this sandbox due blocked RPC, so exact expected ETH amount must be confirmed in a live run.\n\n## Recommended exploit plan (step-by-step)\n\n1. Confirm proxy storage and runtime implementation address on fork (EIP1967 slot + project-specific impl slot).\n2. Enumerate candidate borrowers with `shortfall > 0` (scan recent borrower/liquidation participants, then query `getAccountLiquidity`).\n3. Enumerate target-held assets:\n   - OErc721 balances held by NFTLiquidation.\n   - Underlying NFT balances and token IDs transferable from NFTLiquidation.\n4. Deploy malicious `oTokenRepay` implementing required IOErc20/IOEther-facing methods with zero-debt/always-success behavior.\n5. Option A (preferred): use real collateral market address with preexisting seized balance, call:\n   - `liquidateWithSingleRepayV2(borrower, oTokenCollateral, maliciousRepay, 0, [], false)`.\n6. Option B: use malicious collateral adapter to force `transferSeizedTokenFresh` to transfer specific NFT IDs from target-held inventory.\n7. Convert received NFTs to ETH using best-liquidity route available at pinned block.\n8. Assert net ETH gain `>= 0.1 ETH` (target: maximize by sweeping all transferable inventory).\n\n## Risk and fallback plans\n- Risk: no borrower with positive shortfall found quickly.\n  - Fallback: widen borrower search window via historical borrow/liquidation events.\n- Risk: `nonReentrant` guard uninitialized (if `_notEntered == false`), causing immediate revert.\n  - Fallback: verify initialization state before coding exploit path.\n- Risk: target has no valuable NFT inventory at pinned block.\n  - Fallback: pivot to any transferable token inventory path exposed by same untrusted external-call surface.\n- Risk: custom token/NFT behavior causes postconditions to revert.\n  - Fallback: use exact implementation-compatible collateral market first (Option A), then adapter strategy.\n\n"}}
